1. What are Neural Networks & the Problem of Learning Non-Linearity//
One of the greatest challenges in deep learning education is understanding the process through which neural networks are able to learn non-linear patterns.
There are many theoretical explanations of this process
however, the specific mechanisms behind how a neural network updates its weights,
the choice and use of activation functions and the decision boundaries of neural networks are largely viewed as abstract processes for many learners.
Using 2D spiral data as our visual representation of key concepts,
this project will provide a means for visually exploring five concepts related to neural network design and training, including neuron design,
forward propagation, loss function, back propagation, and the choice of depth and activation function.
By observing the evolution of the decision boundary during training,
we will gain a better understanding of the effect that architectural decisions have on the resultant decision boundary.


2. Assignments and Procedures//
Organize three interwoven coils of information in two-dimensional space (x,y)
—> a linear classifier cannot classify these data; therefore, the hidden layers of the network will teach it about non-linear borders.

Model Design
Input: Two-dimensional coordinates (x,y)
Two or four hidden layers with 100 units each
Output: Three classes of softmax
Loss: Cross-entropy
Conceptual Basis
Neuron Model
Each artificial neuron computes a weighted total of inputs and adds a bias value,
followed by the application of a non-linear activation.
This closely resembles the biological neurons in which the dendrite,
soma and axon represent the pathways of information transmission through the neuron.

Hidden Layer Function
The hidden layer reconfigures the input space stepwise to adapt the data to correspond to linear separability.
A higher number of hidden layers provides opportunities for the network to create higher-order features from the input data.

_Activation Functions_
Function / Range / Key Property / Limitation 
ReLU[0, ∞) / Fast convergence, sparse / Dying ReLU
Sigmoid(0, 1) / Probabilistic output / Vanishing gradients
Tanh(−1, 1) / Zero-centered / Saturates at extremes
Leaky ReLU(−∞, ∞) / Fixes dying ReLU / α is a hyperparameter
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Forward Propagation
Data flows layer by layer: h⁽ˡ⁾ = σ( W⁽ˡ⁾ · h⁽ˡ⁻¹⁾ + b⁽ˡ⁾ )

Loss Function
Cross-Entropy loss measures prediction error: L = −Σ yᵢ · log(ŷᵢ)

Backpropagation & Gradient Descent
Weights are updated via chain rule gradients: W ← W − η · ∂L/∂W.
Learning rate η controls step size — too large causes divergence, too small causes slow convergence.


3. Experimental Studies//
The aim of this study was to investigate the relationship between the number of hidden layers in a network
and the ability of the network to learn the specified classification task.

-The first experiment studies a single hidden layer (one layer deep) against
four hidden layers (four layers deep) to observe how the expressiveness of the newly learned decision boundary increases with increased depth in the model.

-The second experiment takes the four-layer deep network that was previously created and compares different types of activation functions
to measure how quickly each converges to the desired solution and to determine which will result in the best overall classification accuracy when using identical training data.


4. Result Analysis//
Depth & Expressiveness
The 1-layer network forms a coarse boundary, failing to resolve tightly wound spiral arms (~72% accuracy).
The 4-layer network wraps the boundary precisely around each arm (~98% accuracy), demonstrating how depth enables composition of complex representations.

Activation Function Impact
ReLU converges fastest (~200 epochs) due to strong, non-saturating gradients.
Tanh converges moderately (~400 epochs) with stable behavior from zero-centered outputs.
Sigmoid is slowest (~700+ epochs) due to vanishing gradients across layers, reaching only ~89% accuracy.

Learning Rate Sensitivity
η = 1.0 caused divergence; η = 0.001 was too slow. Optimal performance was achieved at η = 0.01 across all activation variants.


5. Conclusion//
The results from this research show that depth is the major influence on representation ability when solving non-linear problems.
On data that has a spiral classification, for example, the four-layered network has provided results of over a 26-point difference
in accuracy than that given by the one-layered network. Additionally, choice of activation function has a significant effect
upon the time to convergence; specifically, the ReLU function had less time to converge than the sigmoid function, which showed
vanishing gradients and greater time to converge due to the increased depth of the architecture.

Through visualisation of the decision boundary, as well as of the loss versus epoch graph,
the previously discussed abstract reasons for how the three items of non-linearity, depth and original gradient-based
optimisation allow for the neural network to learn to represent very complex data sets in a manner that affords flexibility for new data sets of similar type/size.

Future research may be undertaken to consider regularisation methods that could impact both the smoothness of the decision boundary, as well as generalisation ability.






